  "prompt": "What is an acid, base, and pH?",
  "response": "An **acid** is a substance that donates protons (H\u207a ions) in a solution. Acids usually have a sour taste and can react with metals and carbonates. Common examples include hydrochloric acid (HCl) and sulfuric acid (H\u2082SO\u2084).\n\nA **base** is a substance that accepts protons or donates hydroxide ions (OH\u207b) in a solution. Bases often have a bitter taste and a slippery feel and can neutralize acids. Examples of bases include sodium hydroxide (NaOH) and ammonia (NH\u2083).\n\n**pH** is a logarithmic scale used to measure the acidity or alkalinity of a solution. The pH scale typically ranges from 0 to 14:\n\n- A pH of less than 7 indicates an acidic solution.\n- A pH of exactly 7 indicates a neutral solution (like pure water).\n- A pH greater than 7 indicates a basic (or alkaline) solution.\n\nEach whole number change in pH represents a tenfold change in hydrogen ion concentration. For example, a solution with a pH of 4 is ten times more acidic than one with a pH of 5.",
